tip.text:
What was once a boozer with a dodgy rep on the Murder Mile has gradually earned its place in people's hearts as a loveable, slightly scruffy community hub with hella soul. There’s been no million-pound facelift here (or however much pub facelifts cost), instead, you’ll find a creaking tavern with plenty of nooks and crannies adorned in random vintage bits and bobs, worn floorboards, log fires and mismatched furniture.

This is a big pub with the intimacy and charm of a small one: where weekly comedy nights are legendary and a late Saturday night pitstop will be rewarded with an unpretentious raucous dance to Wham or suchlike. Add in one of the biggest beer gardens in East and you’ve got yourself all you require from a neighbourhood boozer.

Found down a narrow-ish street amongst the bustle of Hackney lies The Gun, everything you want your local boozer to be and more. In some form or another the pub itself has been serving pints of the good stuff for Hackney patrons since 1860, but in its latest guise The Gun offers hearty food, locally sourced ales and spirits, arguably the city's greatest pub quiz, and some of the best pub dogs to stroke in all of LDN.

They also welcome a weekly rotation of some of London's finest DJ talent all in the confines of a cozy east end drinkery; with DJs spinning from Thursday to Sunday and dancing heavily encouraged. From tropical disco for your end of week celebration to Sunday selections to calm your soul, The Gun offers a night on the tiles without taking a big knock to your bank balance.

This boozer is a favourite with Clapton locals for its extensive beer selection, jazzed up pub grub, and - most importantly - its beer garden. It’s big, green, shady and sunny in appropriate amounts and full of Clapton’s finest chilling out on deck chairs. On a cold day you could do a lot worse than propping up the bar inside or nabbing one of the chesterfield sofas for a little tête-à-tête.

Food is seen to with tapas-style sharing bits like Padron peppers, chorizo croquettes and the like; Sunday roasts with a good veggie and vegan options; burgers and plenty of nawty desserts too.

Self proclaimed "friendly Hackney pub", this handsome Victorian boozer is run by Norwegians, and decorated with candlelit antiques, unique collectibles, and a moose head.

Go for foreign film nights, ladies nights, a competitive pub quiz, and a rock, paper, scissors night - you heard that correctly. You're sure to be involuntary signed up to whatever's going on by the staff, but you'll succumb to the idea when you realise how much fun they're all having. There is also a beer garden with blankets for you to snuggle up in if it's chilly. Cringe or just the right side of organised fun? Erm you guys take this one.

listing.name: Pub On The Park
listing.subtitle: Vibey Pub with a Huge Garden

tip.text:
Pub on the Park is an absolute classic in the area and there's several reasons for this. It's a lively spot right on London Fields, with outdoor decking overlooking the park. It also tends to show the big games on huge screens, and serves up plenty of savoury pub grub - think burgers, fish and chips, nachos, salads and more.

So it can get pretty chock-a' with other good-time folk like yourself. Good to know then that you can ask for your beer in a plastic cup and take it out onto the field. There's even a flood lit boules court to let the games carry on into the night.

OK we've seen the look on your face. How can a pub be 100% vegan, you're wondering. Well it pretty much means that, wherever possible, all the trimmings (food, drinks, fixtures and fittings) are plant-based and sustainably sourced.

Food is seen to by Club Mexicana which means tacos, nachos and burritos piled high with guacamole, tomatillo salsa, sour cream, pink onions, pickled chillies, chimichurri, fresh lime and coriander. Sounds tingly and tasty right? Our fave was the tofish sandwich which went down a treat. Wash all that down with cask ales (without the fish bits), Beavertown beer, small batch wines and some tasty cocky Ts.

We also popped by for brunch and devoured some tangy, spicy chick'n waffles with chilli maple and bacon (as decadent as it sounds); a full Mexican breakfast with all the plant-based trimmings; some fried tortillas with cherries and cream; and more cocktails that we'd care to admit. It's very on trend, for sure, but it's got the flavour chops to back itself.

Kitchen closed on Mondays.

Before passing the doors at Spurstowe Arms, take a quick look and make sure you’re wearing your Sunday best. Because the Hackneyites who typically frequent this one seem to generally be a) well-dressed and b) pretty damn attractive. If that doesn't deter, or you fancy yourself up to assimilating, you'll find a super cosy, aged tavern with plenty of vintage charm.

A one room joint dominated by a central bar, you'll spot fresh flowers, candles, wonky lights, refurbished mirrors, vintage paintings and art deco posters. It's effortlessly cool, silently saying, 'Oh what, this thing? We just found it’. There are a few ales on tap but nothing out of the ordinary, and the food is pointed towards gastro, with bar food, sharing boards and a couple of mains changing each month.

What this is, though, is either the physical embodiment of a hangover cure or a venue for a group chill, where you can get together either in the walled - and often busy - beer garden out back, or on a candlelit corner table and enjoy a booze-aided commune.

This industrial-chic lounge bar and restaurant may look out of your wallet’s league, but on opening the menu you'll be in for a nice surprise.

Serving great value lunches (try the grilled mackerel salad with fennel and apple slaw for £7), dinners and cocktails around the clock, this is the kind of neighbourhood place you'll find yourself nipping back to regularly. It was the classic Tom Collins-inspired drinks menu with over 40 variations that got our heads turnings - go for the Cognac Blazer Collins for all the tastes of Christmas in one glass, minus the turkey.

Formerly the rather ramshackle London Fields Pub, this building has had a significant refurb to become Martello Hall: a three storey townhouse that serves as a cocktail bar, restaurant, workspace and on-the-go coffeehouse. Plenty of dough has been spent on the stripped-back decor and vintage furniture, and the result is a pretty swanky and classy joint.

Food wise, it's mostly Italian fare with sharing plates and a wood fire oven for delicious pizzas. We'd particularly recommend the Number 7, with roast squash & beetroot, ricotta, hazelnuts, beetroot pesto, mint and kale. Upstairs, you'll find a cosy lounge area with decks and a cocktail bar, which seems an ideal place to woo and be wooed as the night unfolds.

What else? You can hot desk here and work, and also grab coffee or sausage roll by the inch from their street hatch.

This Victorian pub is slightly hidden away down a side street but crammed full of charm. It's on the more stylish end of the pub scale, with the prerequisite dark green quilted seating and a touch of taxidermy.

Good old Arthur lays on a top selection of local beers - this is Hackney after all. Hop down in your Sunday best for a vegan roast, Hereford beef, Old Spot pork belly, or a cornbread stuffed whole roast chicken for two. See you there.

If you've ever pondered what would happen if you set up a pub in Hackney and devoted it to British folk culture and fiery cider, then we are here to put your wandering mind at ease. Hand of Glory, a little off the beaten track on Amhurst Road, is an eccentric spot featuring giant maypoles, wicker masks, brass icons and a straw bear. You can dip your beak on countryside ciders or ales and peck your beak (?) on gourmet hot dogs, burgers and salads.

A good pub to stay all afternoon on a Sunday enjoying a roast served from the open kitchen. The front of the pub is more relaxed, with board games and a great selection of beers and spirits. The decor is quite subtly eccentric until you see the urinals shaped like red lips!

The Cat and Mutton is undeniably Broadway Market's top dog, bringing the cream of the market inside. This is a pub known for switching up its menu frequently with a great mix of sharing plates and weekly specials. If you're lucky enough to steal a table on a Sunday go for a roast, beef and horseradish cream or miso aubergine for veggies.

Need a sweetener to the deal? Live music all through the week, and sets from DJs at the weekend (free entry too).

Butcher by day, restaurant by night, Hill & Szrok is like some kind of dual-identity meaty superhero. It's definitely an experience eating here - everyone sits round one massive communal table (a butcher's block during the day), and can choose from a small range of premium beef cuts, lamb racks, or duck breasts. Sides are there to jazz things up and you should look no further (if it's on the menu) than the blood orange and celery leaf salad.

FYI - Hill & Szrok do not take reservations.

Sitting in The Dove strangely reminds us of sitting below deck on a pirate ship. Maybe we've done that in a past life or something - it would certainly explain the scurvy. It's a dark and atmospheric tavern full of dark wood, candles and Hackney sorts sinking Belgian beers; a pub that's made for those winter nights that leave you scampering for cosiness and beer. Both are in abundance here with a huge selection of world beer, real ales and guest ales from micro craft-brewers.

The food here is also not just a passing thought. They have their own dining room which serves up an array of pub classics along with Thai specialities and that's without mentioning their Sunday Roast, known by those in the know to be one of the best you can find in this neck of the woods.

Some say you can only trust a pub that brews their own beer. Well thankfully this one does and has tailored each of their 'People's Pints' to sit perfectly on your boozy pallets.

It's also pretty well known for its blossoming beer garden - with heaters, huts and lawns, it's a great hang-out spot all year round. Food is seen to with all the good BBQ bits and some lighter salad options. Burgers range from pulled pork and cajun chicken, to goat's cheese or vegan; Sunday roasts come with all the trimmings and beer is crafty as heck. They even do a bottomless boozy brunch featuring mimosas and the like on a Saturday. A real pub of the people, eh?

Oldroyd restaurant in Islington is a proper Dojo fave, so hearing about the Duke of Richmond by the very same Tom Oldroyd had us pumped. And we weren't wrong, this renovated pub has had just the right kind of refurb. A lick of paint here, some green velvet chairs there and a darn sexy original tile floor.

There's two areas, the boozy bit filled with the prerequisite craft beer and burgers, and the dining room dishing out prime selects to the fancy kind of pub goer. We'll be roughing it with nawty crab and chip butties (yep, they are real) but you can tuck into butter-poached salmon with clams, samphire and wild fennel if you're so inclined.

Just down the road from Victoria Park, this cosy, traditional pub is spot on for post park walks - in summer take a pew in the beer garden out front or in winter cosy up inside. The walls are lined with rural curiosities such as a framed pike and peasants, the bar is nice and old and there's often a jazz band tinkling away in the corner. On Sundays they serve a mean roast and throughout the week is a selection of pub classics.

Oh and as a little extra, they have an art gallery upstairs showcasing the work of local artists.

The Axe is a little like that handsome kid at school who just seemed to excel at every kind of sport, evoking a little admiration and plenty of bitching from its peers. Because everything at this Stokey local is right on: it's stylish yet retains a cosy, traditionally pubby vibe; it boasts an insanely extensive craft beer collection (60 on offer, 22 on tap) served up from the centrepiece square bar; top-notch gourmet food (including a killer Sunday roast); and a serene nook of a beer garden that’s all pine wood and plants.

It’s that stalwart neighbourhood boozer which lures in all sorts: from craft beer nerds to groups of pals looking to set up shop for an all-day affair; where the noisy jabbering of people filling up on quality beer and quality food fills the air, caught up in the pure essence of pub life.

The White Hart is all about the community spirit. It makes a good meeting point for sports fans, ale aficionados, dog lovers and people with prams (with children in them). In winter you'll be cosy-ed up on the chesterfield sofa by the fire with an IPA and a flakey sausage roll to munch on. And in summer? You'll most likely by living it up in the beer garden - basically an amazing country pub garden, covered in ivy and roses.

Their traditional Sunday roasts, come with all the trimmings your gran used to make and then some - think honey glazed pork belly or roast lamb with mint sauce, baby. Expect DJs on Fridays, live bands, and a pub quiz every Wednesday for the geeks.
